                    <td width="100%" bgcolor="#CACAFF"><font face="Verdana" size="2"><b>Banking sector performance 2002</b></font></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td width="100%" bgcolor="#ECECFF">
                      <blockquote>
                        <p><font face="Verdana" size="1"> In line with the global trend, domestic money supply continued to increase. Easy money conditions had its scaling down impact on money market, deposit and lending interest rates. Commercial bank deposits expanded as compared to credit. Owing to gradual fall in interest rates, demand deposits showed greater expansion trend as compared to time deposits, underlying the preference of the depositors to stay at the lower end of the duration looking for signs of stabilisation and firming up of interest rates. The generally stable personal loan interest rate also was impacted by easy money conditions, with the rate falling to around nine per cent in the case of selective customers from the ceiling of 12 per
                        cent.<br>
                        The drive against money laundering was made further stringent with the introduction of The Money Laundering Law in April 2002. Similarly the practice of corporate governance in banks was further strengthened with the CBO laying down broad, clear-cut principles of demarcation between the role, responsibility and accountability of the board of directors and that of the management in
                        banks.<br>
                        Also, number of banks expanded and upgraded their electronic banking services by providing tele and Internet banking solutions to the customers. Utility bill payment service through ATMs covered more banks. ATMs of the various banks were inter- linked with the provision of Oman switch service. Few more banks became members of the Muscat Securities Market and offered brokerage services to their customers. The primary market was showing signs of revival with the number of issues lead managed by the banks increased during the year. The year began with the merger of Industrial Bank of Oman with BankMuscat and the year ended with the merger of Majan International Bank and Bank
                        Dhofar.<br>
                        With improved asset quality, growth in business and favourable interest rate conditions, banking sector as a whole is expected to report good results for
                        2002.</font></p>
                      </blockquote>
